abstract = {Health is more than medical care: 89% of health occurs outside the clinical space through genetics, behaviour, environment and social circumstances. A healthy lifestyle, including physical activity and exercise, is increasingly seen as an important component of the physical, mental, and overall well-being of patients with neuromuscular diseases (NMD). No medication can positively influence as many organ systems as physical activity and exercise. The positive effect of exercise appears to be even more significant in NMD than in the healthy population: an increasing number of trials show that exercise can slow down disease progression. Exercise is not a medicine but a lifestyle. It will have to be applied for as long as possible. It is important to let patients adhere to an active lifestyle from an early age to take full advantage of this effect. Understanding the underlying mechanisms that explain the beneficial effects of exercise in NMD is fundamental to optimising exercise interventions in general and tailoring optimal interventions to single patients. Possible underlying mechanisms of effect lie in inhibiting inflammation, epigenetics and on the mental level: positively implementing exercise can increase patients' self-efficacy. Physical activity as part of psychological treatment has been proven to be an effective intervention in several studies. But we are still far from there: there is a great need for research into the underlying mechanisms of effect, which can also be helpful in the development of medication. Finally, there is still much to be gained in tailor-made exercises to prevent over- and under-exertion.}
